  <h2 id="what-is-machining-coolant">What is Machining Coolant?</h2>

  <p>Dolphin Centrifuge, based in Warren, Michigan, supplies purpose-built disc stack centrifuge systems for this application at 7000 Gs with separation down to 1 microns. Machining coolant (also called metalworking fluid) is a water-based emulsion used in <strong>metal cutting, grinding, milling, drilling, and turning</strong> operations to cool the tool-workpiece interface, reduce friction, and flush metal chips from the cutting zone. The most common types are soluble oils, semi-synthetic fluids, and fully synthetic coolants &mdash; all mixed with water at concentrations typically ranging from 5% to 15%.
  </p>

  <p>
    During machining operations, coolant becomes contaminated with <strong>metal fines</strong> (swarf), <strong>tramp oil</strong> from machine tool hydraulics and slideway lubricants, and <strong>bacteria</strong> that thrive in the warm, nutrient-rich fluid. Without continuous purification, coolant degrades rapidly &mdash; producing foul odors, causing skin irritation, shortening tool life, and degrading part surface finish.
  </p>

  <p>
    Coolant replacement is expensive: not only does fresh coolant concentrate cost significantly, but spent coolant must be treated as <strong>hazardous waste</strong> in most jurisdictions. Extending coolant life through centrifugal purification delivers substantial savings in both coolant purchases and disposal costs.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Coolant Centrifuge ── -->
  <h2 id="coolant-centrifuge">Coolant Centrifuge</h2>

  <p>
    A coolant centrifuge is a <strong>disc stack centrifuge</strong> specifically configured for continuous removal of tramp oil and metal fines from water-based machining coolants. Unlike coalescers, skimmers, or filters, a disc stack centrifuge performs <strong>three-phase separation</strong> in a single pass &mdash; simultaneously removing both floating tramp oil and sinking metal particles from the coolant.
  </p>

  <p>
    The centrifuge operates in a <strong>kidney-loop</strong> configuration, continuously drawing contaminated coolant from the machine sump or central system, purifying it, and returning clean coolant. This arrangement keeps coolant at peak performance without interrupting machining operations.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    Dolphin Centrifuge supplies turnkey coolant purification systems from 3 GPM for individual machines to 50 GPM for central coolant systems serving entire production lines.
  </blockquote>

  <!-- ── Operation ── -->
  <h2 id="operation">How a Coolant Centrifuge Operates</h2>

  <p>
    The centrifuge bowl spins at high speed, generating centrifugal forces exceeding <strong>7,000 Gs</strong>. At this force level, contaminant particles as small as <strong>1 micron</strong> are separated from the coolant. The disc stack inside the bowl creates thin fluid layers between closely spaced conical discs, dramatically reducing the distance particles must travel to be captured.
  </p>

  <p>
    Contaminated coolant enters the centrifuge through a central feed tube and is distributed between the disc stack. Under intense centrifugal force, the three phases separate according to density:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Heavy phase (metal fines and sludge):</strong> Moves outward to the bowl periphery where it accumulates until ejected</li>
    <li><strong>Light phase (tramp oil):</strong> Moves inward and exits through the light-phase outlet</li>
    <li><strong>Clean coolant:</strong> Exits through the heavy-phase (water) outlet and returns to the sump or central system</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In <strong>self-cleaning models</strong>, accumulated sludge is automatically ejected at timed intervals through ports in the bowl wall. This allows continuous, unattended operation &mdash; critical for 24/7 machining environments. Manual-clean models are available for lower-volume applications where periodic manual bowl cleaning is acceptable.
  </p>

